subSubSection.paragraph:
Oligosoma kakerakau


sp. nov.

is diurnal and strongly heliothermic, and is most often observed basking or foraging in light wells (
Figure 4
), particularly during humid conditions (
Gillanders 2017
). The habitat within its area of occupancy is a mixture of broadleaf forest, low scrub and low groundcover (
Wiles 2014
). 

Oligosoma kakerakau


sp. nov.

occurs in all of these habitats, but is most common in low scrub and groundcover probably because these habitats provide a greater number of basking opportunities (
Barr 2014
; 
Wiles 2014
). Similarly they are known to occur only on the ridgetop and north facing slopes, and have never been detected on the shady south facing slopes at Bream Head (
Wiles 2014
).
